S'(H\xc3\xa5kan Svensson / Wikimedia)I\xe2\x80\x99m over at\xc2\xa0First Things today, talking about why people may want to drop barriers to Communion out of fear of excluding the people who most need strength and support, and offering suggestions for other ways to see, know, and love our pewmates:Communion is often the sign of acceptance that people seek\xe2\x80\x94not just because it\xe2\x80\x99s at the heart of the faith, but because it may be the only form of love that people know how to ask for or see offered at their parish.In many parishes, it\xe2\x80\x99s easy to attend church anonymously, without speaking to anyone else except for a quick \xe2\x80\x9cHave a nice day, Father\xe2\x80\x9d and without any contact with fellow parishioners beyond a quick handshake at the sign of peace. A \xe2\x80\x9cHi\xe2\x80\x9d from a greeter at the door can be nice, but it doesn\xe2\x80\x99t really give people a sense of being known in the \xe2\x80\x9cJesus looked at him and loved him\xe2\x80\x9d sense. Communion is asked to do all the work of inclusion.[...]Churches can include more\xc2\xa0\xe2\x80\x9cWinter Christian\xe2\x80\x9d\xc2\xa0themes in homilies and hymns.\xc2\xa0Winter Christians are both intensely engaged with their faith, but also intensely stymied by spiritual dryness, doubts, a persistent sin, or some other difficulty. (They\xe2\x80\x99re unlike \xe2\x80\x9cSummer Christians\xe2\x80\x9d who are joyfully drawn to the faith, and completely unlike people who like or dislike the church, but don\xe2\x80\x99t yearn for it). The psalms of lament sound familiar to them, but \xe2\x80\x9chis yoke is easy, and his burden is light\xe2\x80\x9d is a little closer to how cartoonist\xc2\xa0Allie Brosh describes attempts to jolly people out of depression:\xc2\xa0\xe2\x80\x9cAre you taunting me? Is this some weird game where you name all the things I can\xe2\x80\x99t do?\xe2\x80\x9dA hymn like\xc2\xa0\xe2\x80\x9cConflict\xe2\x80\x9d\xc2\xa0from the Shenandoah Harmony collection of shape note songs is much closer to their experience. (\xe2\x80\x9cIt\xe2\x80\x99s seldom I can ever see / Myself as I would wish to be / What I desire I can\xe2\x80\x99t attain / From what I hate, I can\xe2\x80\x99t refrain.\xe2\x80\x9d). It may not be the end of the Gospel story, but it\xe2\x80\x99s part of most people\xe2\x80\x99s experience of it over their lives. Leaving it out is like having Easter without Lent.Read more at First Things\xe2\x80\xa6'
