r practice at the end of alumni debates, on the way home from bars with friends, etc. \xc2\xa0Having a regular practice helps keep me on track, and also gives me something to be hospitable with.Choosing a prayer rule is the kind of challenge that can be derailed by the desire to get it\xc2\xa0right, and therefore put off beginning. \xc2\xa0In general, I think it makes sense to start with\xc2\xa0something (maybe even this evening, if you have a candidate in mind) and to revise as you go, if needed. \xc2\xa0And it\xe2\x80\x99s a good idea to pick something you are pretty sure you can do, even if it means you\xe2\x80\x99re picking something that feels too small (an\xc2\xa0Anima Christi when you wake up and before bed?)I figure that I\xe2\x80\x99ll do a better job of reflecting on my prayer life when I\xe2\x80\x99m actually praying, because I have more opportunities to be attentive to God working in my life. \xc2\xa0It\xe2\x80\x99s a relationship, and I can\xe2\x80\x99t do much if I\xe2\x80\x99m pushing the other person out until I come up with a solution in isolation. So I\xe2\x80\x99d say just start somewhere, and assume you\xe2\x80\x99re picking something flawed, but that you\xe2\x80\x99ll work it out as you go. \xc2\xa0 To crib from\xc2\xa0Company, \xe2\x80\x9cIt\xe2\x80\x99s much better living it than looking at it.\xe2\x80\x9dBut that process of revising/discernment can be pretty stressful and self-conscious. \xc2\xa0It\xe2\x80\x99s often hard for me to know whether something I\xe2\x80\x99m trying isn\xe2\x80\x99t working out and I should move on or whether I should try to change myself to fit the practice. \xc2\xa0I noticed that both Rod and Ken referenced spiritual directors, and it\xe2\x80\x99s harder to pick up a prayer rule (or find your way into ascetic practices\xe2\x80\x93which they also recommended) without one.Eve Tushnet calls this the danger of \xe2\x80\x9cself abboting.\xe2\x80\x9dI talk about one part of this problem a little bit in the book, in the section on accountability. Lack of accountability was/is one of my own biggest struggles as a celibate layperson. It played a serious role in my drinking problem\xe2\x80\x93there was nobody to come home to, there was a possibility of\xc2\xa0privacy\xc2\xa0which was tempting and damaging. I think this is one reason that starting spiritual direction was so foundational to my recovery and eventual sobriety. I basically went out and got myself an abbot.One reason I\xe2\x80\x99m so high on the idea of people\xc2\xa0living with their parents/families of origin, or in a family household, is that it allows laypeople to be one another\xe2\x80\x99s abbots, to guide and watch over one another. It requires adherence to rules, sometimes-sacrificial consideration of others\xe2\x80\x99 needs, and a surrender of one\xe2\x80\x99s own comfort, preferences, and autonomy. Intentional community living, which gets a nice chapter in the book, is another way to attain some of the spiritual benefits of monastic life.In the absence of an abbot of my own, my approach tends to be a bit Miss Frizzle-ish: \xe2\x80\x9cTake chances, make mistakes, get messy!\xe2\x80\x9d \xc2\xa0I\xe2\x80\x99m willing to try a lot of small scale, temporary things and try to figure out what might be helpful, rather than try to plan out a really good idea and then commit. \xc2\xa0It helps a lot to be able to reach out to friends and learn from their experience and their knowledge of me (which can be more clear-eyed than my self knowledge).So, maybe the best thing to do today is to try out some kind of regular prayer (if you don\xe2\x80\x99t already) and to invite a friend to dinner in two weeks to catch up and kibbitz about what you\xe2\x80\x99re trying.\xc2\xa0'
