80\x94 places that Earth bacteria might happily call home. (InSight, NASA\xe2\x80\x99s next Mars lander, to be launched in March, and the next rover, to be launched in 2020, will also not be sterilized. In considering landing sites for the 2020 rover, NASA has crossed off those in special regions.)[...]Areas treated as special regions include the periodic dark streaks known as recurrent slope lineae \xe2\x80\x94 R.S.L.s for short \xe2\x80\x94 spotted on the sides of craters, canyons and mountains. Scientists last week said they were generated by the percolating of liquid water, one of the essentials for life.The caution brings up a Catch-22. NASA at present cannot explore the places with the greatest potential for life \xe2\x80\x94 one that could come into play for Curiosity, which is slowly climbing a mountain in Gale Crater.\xe2\x80\x94 4 \xe2\x80\x94Speaking of Mars, I want to recommend\xc2\xa0The Martian. \xc2\xa0When I came home from seeing it, I was so excited I just blurted to the doorman at my building that he should see it, and he told me I was the third person that night to tell him. \xc2\xa0It left me feeling very \xe2\x80\x9cEff yeah, engineering! \xc2\xa0Eff yeah, humans!\xe2\x80\x9dThe book is great, and I certainly think reading it first deepened my enjoyment of the movie (since it gets a bit more detailed about all the MacGyvering the protagonist does) but I think you\xe2\x80\x99ll enjoy it a lot either way.(It\xe2\x80\x99s also just fun to watch a movie that I contrasted with\xc2\xa0Gravity by saying \xe2\x80\x9cYou know how in\xc2\xa0Gravity, running out of air is a metaphor for the way the protagonist needs to decide to live fully again? \xc2\xa0In\xc2\xa0The Martian, it\xe2\x80\x99s a metaphor for RUNNING OUT OF AIR\xe2\x80\x9d\xe2\x80\x94 5 \xe2\x80\x94Salon has a nice piece on how the KGB caught CIA operatives. \xc2\xa0The CIA was convinced they must be using moles, but, in fact they were mostly using logic and observation:Back in Moscow he began systematically combing the KGB archives for consistent patterns observable in the postings of CIA counterparts. The research was extended to take in the records of the KGB\xe2\x80\x99s allies, Cuba and the Warsaw Pact. The open source literature from the United States was also exploited to the full. And wherever possible access was obtained to data compiled by the local police authorities.What Totrov came up with were 26 unchanging indicators as a model for identifying U.S. intelligence officers overseas. Other indicators of a more trivial nature could be detected in the field by a vigilant foreign counterintelligence operative but not uniformly so: the fact that CIA officers replacing one another tended to take on the same post within the embassy hierarchy, drive the same make of vehicle, rent the same apartment and so on. Why? Because the personnel office in Langley shuffled and dealt overseas postings with as little effort as required.\xe2\x80\x94 6 \xe2\x80\x94Speaking of the art of deduction, the BBC released its trailer for the\xc2\xa0Sherlock\xc2\xa0Christmas special. \xe2\x80\x94 7 \xe2\x80\x94I really like that fanfic impulses are going mainstream. \xc2\xa0If the\xc2\xa0Sherlock showrunners (who are already writing AU fic) want to put their take on the characters in\xc2\xa0another AU, I say go for it! \xc2\xa0So I\xe2\x80\x99m also pleased by the exuberance of the below: For more Quick Takes, visit Conversion Diary!'
