S'\xe2\x80\x94 1 \xe2\x80\x94A friend of mine is looking for good semi-pregnant Halloween costumes (she\xe2\x80\x99s not big enough to go as a globe, as she hoped). \xc2\xa0I don\xe2\x80\x99t have that much to suggest (maybe you all have ideas for her?) but I do have a roundup of excellent parent-baby costumes. \xc2\xa0My favorite is the child as Max from\xc2\xa0Where the Wild Things Are, and his mom as his boat!\xc2\xa0\xe2\x80\x94 2 \xe2\x80\x94Also in the domain of, um,\xc2\xa0expressive things to do with your offspring: there\xe2\x80\x99s an annual reunion for people named after Paul William Bryant, a famous football coach in Alabama.\xe2\x80\x94 3 \xe2\x80\x94This first-person essay on fraternities is a more sober story about being swept up in college enthusiasm/identities:The great paradox of Greek life is that the people who are constantly pushing you, sometimes gently, sometimes not, to engage in behaviors that can kill you do not actually want you to die. When someone encourages you to drink yourself unconscious, then grabs a magic marker to draw a pair of open eyes on your comatose lids, ejaculating penises on your pallid cheeks, four-letter words on your clammy forehead, they do so believing that you will eventually wake up and have a good laugh at their work. No one does any of that while also believing that you are on the verge of death.\xe2\x80\x94 4 \xe2\x80\x94Communities can be formed in less intense, less dangerous circumstances. \xc2\xa0I like prefer the emotional rush of communal singing to that of shared danger, so I really enjoyed Audra Nakes\xe2\x80\x99s essay in Ethika Politka:\xc2\xa0Yet even most cities and regions that do exhibit strong local identities don\xe2\x80\x99t seem to have a culture of singing. I\xe2\x80\x99m not the only one who feels that something is missing. As I was writing this piece, someone in my parish young adult group invited all of us to his house to sing folk songs and spirituals and sent the repertoire in advance so that we could familiarize ourselves with the songs. My friend\xe2\x80\x99s organized effort underscores not only the lack of a singing culture in the United States, but also that the desire to sing together persists. No matter how much Americans value individualism, we\xe2\x80\x99re still social animals who long for outward expressions of communion with others, particularly those with whom we share a national or patriotic identity.\xe2\x80\x94 5 \xe2\x80\x94While we\xe2\x80\x99re speaking of singing and culture, I heartily recommend this Storify collecting my friend Ivan\xe2\x80\x99s tweets on how\xc2\xa0Hamilton\xc2\xa0does an unusually good job telling a war story:Artistic works about warfare in the past are usually really bad at conveying the heft of tactical planning. @HamiltonMusical nails it.\xe2\x80\x94 Ivan Plis (@ivanplis) September 22, 2015Read the whole thing here.\xe2\x80\x94 6 \xe2\x80\x94Hamilton\xc2\xa0is as much about how history gets told as it\xe2\x80\x99s about the specific story it\xe2\x80\x99s telling. \xc2\xa0In Japan, where the oral testimony of atomic bomb survivors has been tremendously important, younger people are trying to practically become a book,\xc2\xa0Fahrenheit\xc2\xa0451-style to keep the stories alive, after their tellers are dead.\xe2\x80\x9cThe denshosha are essentially putting themselves in the position of that person, so the survivor doesn\xe2\x80\x99t permanently disappear,\xe2\x80\x9d he said. They have an authority that comes with the survivor\xe2\x80\x99s blessing to be \xe2\x80\x9cheirs\xe2\x80\x9d to their stories, he said, and a mandate to keep finding audiences. Survivors often visit schools, for instance, something denshosha could do in their place.\xe2\x80\x9cIt\xe2\x80\x99s a very interesting experiment in forming and preserving collective memories,\xe2\x80\x9d Professor Kawanishi said.\xe2\x80\x94 7 \xe2\x80\x94Finally, here\xe2\x80\x99s the last of the pieces I wrote for DeSales media during the Papal visit: \xe2\x80\x9cEmbracing the Demands of Priesthood, and Demanding the Embrace of Priests\xe2\x80\x9dHis visit may inspire Catholics to be more demanding, in just the way he desires. Just as people shamelessly run up to the Pope to ask for his blessing and his prayers, they may also run up to their parish priest to ask for his prayers, his blessings, and his presence. In all of these small, humble things, a priest pours himself out for his people.Pope Francis encouraged the bishops to find ways to support their priests, so that they have the strength to welcome all the needs of their people. After he leaves, it will be up to us to have the courage to offer our needs to our priests, in ordinary times, as easily as we do during the festival of the pope\xe2\x80\x99s visit.\xc2\xa0For more Quick Takes, visit Conversion Diary!'
